    <p>
        UDP is typically used by applications that do not want the overhead that comes with reliable transmission as well as applications that can tolerate <em>some</em> packet loss. 
        VOIP and video-chat services are examples of applications that might employ UDP as their transmission protocol. In VOIP, some packet loss is tolerable because 
        there is a continuous stream of data being sent as voice is being processed and sent over the network.
    </p>

    <h2>TCP</h2>
    <p>
        <abbr title="Transmission Control Protocol">TCP</abbr> is another transport layer protocol that comes with a few bells and whistles. 
        As opposed to UDP, TCP offers reliable service and is connection-based. In addition to that, TCP also has some built-in congestion control 
        mechanisms that make it preferable to use if a network link if facing a high level of congestion.
    </p>

    <p>
        A common use of TCP is in something we're already familiar with, HTTP! TCP is the protocol that makes web browsing possible. 
        It provides the reliable data transfer necessary for web browsers to retrieve web pages from servers. The connection-based service it offers 
        also allows the existence of persistent connections used by browsers to speed up our browsing. Only accounting for HTTP, we see that TCP
        is indispensible for a well-functioning internet.
    </p>

